I executed this jupyter notebook in a MacBook Pro 8GB and I had some trouble reading the files consecutively. Therefore, it is advised to restart the kernel after each file is loaded because they take a lot of space in the memory of the computer.

In the first part, it is presented a reading test using four different methods, which should be run one by one as explained before. In order to create the yaml and python files, and run the validation steps, this jupyter notebook can be started from step 2.

Dataset Sumary

  • This dataset presents 27 columns (variables) and 17111358 rows (registers).
  • The file size is: 3.7 GB

1. Test: reading a 2GB file using different methods of file reading¶

An experiment to test the read csv functions of the pakcages pandas, moding, dask and ray was performed and the time to load measured.

In order to run this jupyter notebook, especially to make the test, it is advised to restart the kernel after the file is loaded using any of the files because it takes a lot of space in the memory of the computer and the following scripts many not run accordingly depending on the configuration of your machine.

In this machine, each test was performed after restarting the kernel but the results of each test can be seen in figures presented right after each test part presented in this document.

Based on the previous analysis, the dask dataframe presented the lowest reading time, followed by ray, pandas and modin. However, the time needed to display the first register of the dataframe was lower for pandas, followed by dask dataframe, modin and ray (in this order). Finally, when a simple function "len()" was applied to the these dataframes, the fastest response was achieved by the dataframe created with pandas, followed by modin and ray (all presented very low times, in the microsecond range). In contrast to that, the dataframe generated with dask presented the highest time to process the function tested (approximately 34s).

The fastest reading tool was the Dask Dataframe, however, the fastest tool to perform data processing was pandas. Therefore, let's use the traditional pandas to read the file to complete the tasks of the following steps.¶

2.2. Creating the csvutility file (csvutility.py)¶

Creating the csvutility file with four functions. The first functions reads the yaml file, which is used to validate the columns of the dataframe (exact same match). The second function is used by the third function to support the formatting of the columns' name. The third function is used to validate the the column names and column length. Finally the last function helps to count the number the columns and rows in the dataframe as well as it also returns the size of the dataframe in memory.

In [20]:
%%writefile csvutility.py
import logging
import os
import subprocess
import yaml
import pandas as pd
import datetime 
import gc
import re


################
# File Reading #
################

def read_config_file(filepath):
    with open(filepath, 'r') as stream:
        try:
            return yaml.safe_load(stream)
        except yaml.YAMLError as exc:
            logging.error(exc)


def replacer(string, char):
    pattern = char + '{2,}'
    string = re.sub(pattern, char, string) 
    return string

def col_header_val(df, table_config):
    '''
    replace whitespaces in the column
    and standardized column names
    '''
    df.columns = df.columns.str.upper()
    df.columns = df.columns.str.replace('[^\w]','_',regex=True)
    df.columns = list(map(lambda x: x.strip('_'), list(df.columns)))
    df.columns = list(map(lambda x: replacer(x,'_'), list(df.columns)))
    expected_col = list(map(lambda x: x.upper(),  table_config['columns']))
    expected_col.sort()
    df.columns =list(map(lambda x: x.upper(), list(df.columns)))
    columns_index = list(df.columns)
    df = df.reindex(sorted(df.columns), axis=1)
    if len(df.columns) == len(expected_col) and list(expected_col) == list(df.columns):
        print("column name and column length validation passed")
        df = df.reindex(columns=columns_index)
        return 1
    
    else:
        print("column name and column length validation failed")
        mismatched_columns_file = list(set(df.columns).difference(expected_col))
        print("Following File columns are not in the YAML file",mismatched_columns_file)
        missing_YAML_file = list(set(expected_col).difference(df.columns))
        print("Following YAML columns are not in the file uploaded",missing_YAML_file)
        logging.info(f'df columns: {df.columns}')
        logging.info(f'expected columns: {expected_col}')
        return 0
    
def file_summary(df):
    '''
    create a summary of the loaded dataframe, including the number of rows,
    number of columns and the size of the file
    '''
    nc = len(df.columns)
    nr = len(df.index)
    mem = sum(df.memory_usage()) 
    print("\nThis dataset presents {} columns (variables) and {} rows (registers).".format(nc, nr))
    
    if mem < 1000:
        print("\nThe file size is: {} bytes".format(mem))
    elif mem < 1000000:
        print("\nThe file size is: {} KB".format(round(mem/1000, 1)))
    elif mem < 1000000000:
        print("\nThe file size is: {} MB".format(round(mem/1000000, 1)))
    elif mem < 1000000000000:
        print("\nThe file size is: {} GB".format(round(mem/1000000000, 1)))
    return 1

def save_pipe_txtgz_file(df, table_config):
    
    output = "data/" + table_config["output_file"] + "." + table_config["output_file_format"] + "." + table_config["compress_type"]
    df.to_csv(output, index=False, sep="|", header=True, chunksize=5000, compression="gzip")

Writing csvutility.py

2.3 Testing the csvutility procedures with 2 datasets¶

These datasets are modifications of the original dataset but with a much smaller size, as it does not influence the check performed in the columns by the created script. We edited the yaml every time the validation was run because diferent files were used as input.

The first dataset presented columns with the same names but presenting a few spaces and special caracteres, such as: "FL#DATE ", "DISTANCE#$%", " DEST___", "AIR TIME", and "TAXI|IN".

The second dataset presented a few columns with changed names, such as FL_DATE to FL_DATA, DISTANCE to DISTANCA. Moreover, there were added two new columns BOARDING_FEE and COMPANY_NAME.
